[10] Ukraine (Kharkov)
Date: Fri 23 May 2014
Source: Objektiv [in Russian, trans. abbreviated Mod.CP, edited]
http://www.objectiv.tv/230514/97894.html


Since the beginning of the month [May 2014], 47 people, including children and a pregnant woman, have been admitted to hospital with a diagnosis of measles virus infection.

Irina Zubkov, a senior infectious disease specialist, stated that the disease had been brought to the city by people of Roma origin visiting relatives in the city. Most of the patients belong to a single Roma community. Doctors have failed to comment, but it is well-established that vaccination is the appropriate method for controlling the disease.

According to Sergei Kuznetsov, Professor, Department of Pediatric Infectious Diseases Hospital KhNMU, unfortunately, Ukraine is not ready to undertake a vaccination campaign because of inadequate preparedness and the need to purchase appropriate vaccine from other countries. Parents must make their own arrangements.

At the present time, 3 children and 7 adults remain in hospital but are expected to be released in the near future. Experts believe that this outbreak of measles will then have been contained.

--
