[11] Russia (Dagestan)
Date: 29 May 2014
Source: RIA Dagestan [in Russian, trans. abbreviated Mod.CP, edited]
http://www.riadagestan.ru/news/health/bolee_500_sluchaev_kori_zaregistrirovano_v_dagestane_s_nachala_goda/


More than 500 cases of measles have been reported in Dagestan since the beginning of the year [2014]. Despite a decline in the incidence of measles at the beginning of February 2014, the epidemic situation with regard to measles in the republic remains critical.

During January to May 2014, 526 confirmed cases of measles were registered in the republic, all confirmed by laboratory tests, giving a measles incidence rate of 18.14 per 100 000 population.

Measles is a particular danger for children under one year old who have not yet received vaccination because of their age and to adults who have not been vaccinated and who are at risk of developing more serious disease. As a consequence of the deteriorating situation in Dagestan, a policy of universal vaccination is being introduced. According to an Order of the Government of the Republic of Dagestan, the Ministry of Health will be allocated funds to purchase 150 000 doses of measles vaccine for supplementary immunisation.

Pursuant to the letter of the Federal Service for Supervision of Consumer Rights Protection and Human Welfare, on 9 Apr 2014: "Additional measles immunization" was carried out from 20-25 May 2014 and included pupils, boarding schools, and secondary vocational educational institutions. Immunization was carried out regardless of prior preventive vaccinations. According to Rospotrebnadzor, by 27 May 2014,
47 803 students had been vaccinated at schools, boarding schools, and secondary vocational education institutions, representing 74 percent of the subject children.

Measles is an acute, highly contagious and infectious viral disease, characterized by general malaise, fever, lesions of the mucous membranes of the eyes, respiratory tract, accompanied by a rash. Measles virus is transmitted from an infected person to a healthy person through sneezing, coughing, talking and even breathing. The only measure to prevent this infection is vaccination, A safe, cheap and stable live vaccine is available globally.

--
